Column Comment.0: SEISMIC SET SUBTYPE: The seismic set type column is used to enforce arelationship between the SEIS SET supertype and its valid sub types. Values for thiscolumn must be the name of the table that is the valid sub type for this row of data.Valid entries include SEIS_LINE, SEIS_SEGMENT, SEIS_SURVEY, SEIS_PLAN,SEIS_WELL, SEIS_PROC_SET, SEIS_INTERP_SET or SEIS_3D.
Column Comment.1: SEISMIC PROCESSING SET: unique identifier for a set of data that will beprocessed as a unit. The processing set may be a single line, a portion of a line, agroup of lines, a 3D survey, a portion of a 3D survey or a compilation of several.Details about what seismic sets are being processed is captured in the table SEISPROC COMPONENT.
Column Comment.2: PROCESSING STEP IDENTIFIER: unique identifier for the processing step.
Column Comment.3: PARAMETER ID: Unique identifier for the parameter applied to this process.
Column Comment.4: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.5: DATE FORMAT DESCRIPTION: Use this column to define the level of precision inthe DATE format colums, such as YYYY, or YYYQQ, or YYYYMM or YYYYMMDD
Column Comment.6: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.7: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.8: PARAMETER DESCRIPTION: text description of the parameter applied, such aswhen the value cannot be expresses as a number.
Column Comment.9: PARAMETER ORIGIN: the original source of the parameter.
Column Comment.10: SEISMIC PROCESSING PARAMETER TYPE NAME: the type or name of theprocessing parameter applied at this step, such as filter, gain etc.
Column Comment.11: PARAMETER UNIT OF MEASURE: unit given to the parameter applied.
Column Comment.12: PARAMETER VALUE 1: the first or upper parameter value applied, such as theupper setting of a band pass filter
Column Comment.13: PARAMETER VALUE 2: the second or lower parameter value applied, such as thelower setting of a band pass filter.
Column Comment.14: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.15: REMARK: Narrative remarks relating to this row of data.
Column Comment.16: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.17: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.18: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.19: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.20: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.21: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.22: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.23: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
